Hello everyone 🙋🏼‍♂️, welcome to the opening chapter of my internship journey at the Environmental Agency of Surabaya (DLH Surabaya). Before delving into the story, I would like to express my gratitude to the Indonesian government, particularly the Ministry of Education, Culture, Research, and Technology, for their outstanding initiative in establishing the MSIB (Certified Internship and Independent Study) program. This program provides invaluable opportunities for university students across Indonesia to enhance and apply their skills while gaining firsthand experience in observing and adapting to the dynamics of professional industries.

Now, let us begin. My internship was conducted on-site at the Environmental Agency of Surabaya (DLH Surabaya), located at Jl. Raya Menur No. 31A, Manyar Sabrangan, Surabaya, East Java. I was assigned to the position of Environmental Pollution Control and worked under the supervision of DLH Surabaya staff. As its name suggests, DLH Surabaya is responsible for environmental management and pollution control, with functions that include policy formulation, monitoring, evaluation, reporting, and public information dissemination. More specifically, the sub-coordinator where I was placed oversees monitoring activities related to air, water, soil, ozone-depleting substances, and carbon stock.

Over the course of four months, my colleagues and I—20 students in total—were engaged in a variety of tasks, ranging from minor assignments to major projects, as well as visits to several government agencies in Surabaya. We also participated in a series of in-class sessions led by outstanding guest speakers. In summary, our responsibilities primarily focused on two areas: monitoring and pollution control. Within the monitoring aspect, we conducted water quality sampling and testing (covering seawater, rivers, and wells), monitored ambient air quality using portable instruments, examined ozone-depleting substances and acid deposition, performed vegetation analyses, and carried out mangrove carbon stock estimations. In terms of pollution control, our role was mainly to identify pollution incidents reported through applications, letters, or social media, and to coordinate appropriate remediation and preventive measures.

During this internship, we were also assigned several group projects. For me, the key projects of this program were particularly significant and can be summarized as follows:

-   **WE (World Environmental) DAY Surabaya 2024**: Environmental awareness program for elementary school students, including talkshows, quizzes, plant distribution, and tree planting.
-   **Kutisari Mud Eruption Study**: Investigation of oil spill causes, impacts, and remediation strategies (soil washing with bio-solvents and phytoremediation using floating wetlands).
-   **Mangrove Carbon Stock Analysis**: Field surveys at Pamurbaya (east coast of Surabaya) and Panturbaya (north coast of Surabaya) to estimate carbon storage capacity.

By the end of the internship, I was deeply grateful for the wide range of knowledge and experience I had gained, which I believe will greatly benefit my future endeavors. These included the development of soft skills such as teamwork, communication, and problem-solving, as well as hard skills such as sampling, laboratory analysis, GIS mapping, and carbon stock estimation. In addition, the internship provided valuable exposure to real-world environmental challenges, opportunities to collaborate with multiple government agencies, and the chance to contribute meaningful data and reports to DLH Surabaya in support of policy development.

